---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="US MEPS Survey — Survey Overview" description="What MEPS is, how it's collected, and what the Panel/Round notation (R3/1, R4/2, R5/3) means before diving into the data">

  <div class="ov-wrap">

    <div class="ov-header">
      <a class="back-crumb" href="/research">← Decoding</a>
      <div class="ov-title-row">
        <h1 class="ov-title">US MEPS Survey — <em>Survey Overview</em></h1>
        <span class="ov-badge">HC-251 · 2023</span>
      </div>
      <p class="ov-desc">
        Before exploring 1,366 variables, a few minutes on where this data comes from and how it's collected —
        especially the <strong>Panel / Round</strong> design, since notation like "R3/1" or "REFPRS31" shows up
        throughout the explorer and doesn't mean anything without this context.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. What is MEPS -->
    <div class="sec-label">01 · What is MEPS</div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        The <strong>Medical Expenditure Panel Survey (MEPS)</strong> is run by the Agency for Healthcare Research
        and Quality (AHRQ) and has collected data every year since 1996. It produces the U.S. government's core
        estimates of health care use, spending, sources of payment, and insurance coverage for the civilian
        noninstitutionalized population.
      </p>
      <p>
        MEPS has two linked parts. The <strong>Household Component (HC)</strong> interviews a nationally
        representative sample of households directly — this is the source for everything in this explorer. The
        <strong>Medical Provider Component (MPC)</strong> separately contacts the pharmacies, doctors, and
        hospitals that HC respondents named, and verifies or fills in payment and drug details the household
        couldn't accurately report themselves — it isn't designed to produce its own national estimates, just to
        improve the HC data.
      </p>
      <p>
        This explorer covers the <strong>2023 Full-Year Consolidated File (HC-251)</strong> — one person per
        record, <strong>18,640</strong> inscope respondents, <strong>1,374</strong> variables spanning
        demographics, income, health status, employment, insurance, and health care utilization/expenditure.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 2. Panel & Round design -->
    <div class="sec-label">02 · The Panel & Round design</div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Each year AHRQ recruits a new <strong>Panel</strong> — a fresh cohort of roughly 15,000 households, drawn
        as a subsample of households that answered the prior year's National Health Interview Survey (NHIS). Every
        household in a panel is then interviewed <strong>5 times ("Rounds")</strong> about 5 months apart, covering
        roughly 2.5 calendar years total, so each panel's data collection straddles two calendar years.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because a new panel starts every year while the previous one is still mid-way through its 5 rounds,
        <strong>two panels are always running at once</strong>, offset by about a year. Any single calendar year's
        data — like 2023 — is stitched together from the <em>second half</em> of one panel and the
        <em>first half</em> of the next.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="timeline-card">
      <div class="timeline-caption">2023 data = Panel 27's later rounds + Panel 28's earlier rounds — the same 3 time slots, from two different panels</div>
      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-label">Panel 27 <span>(started 2022)</span></div>
          <div class="tl-track tl-track-5">
            <div class="tl-bar tl-gray">R1</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-gray">R2</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-2023">R3</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-2023">R4</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-2023">R5</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-row">
          <div class="tl-label">Panel 28 <span>(started 2023)</span></div>
          <div class="tl-track tl-track-5">
            <div class="tl-bar tl-empty"></div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-empty"></div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-2023">R1</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-2023">R2</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-2023">R3</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-row tl-pair-row">
          <div class="tl-label"></div>
          <div class="tl-track tl-track-5">
            <div class="tl-bar tl-pair-lbl"></div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-pair-lbl"></div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-pair-lbl">"R3/1"</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-pair-lbl">"R4/2"</div>
            <div class="tl-bar tl-pair-lbl">"R5/3"</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="timeline-legend"><span class="tl-dot tl-2023-dot"></span> Rounds contributing to the 2023 Consolidated file (HC-251) used in this explorer</div>
      <div class="timeline-note">Simplified — slots are sequential ~5-month interview waves, not drawn to exact calendar scale.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        That's the whole trick behind the "R3/1", "R4/2", "R5/3" notation and variable suffixes like
        <code>REFPRS31</code>: the first digit is Panel 27's round number, the second is Panel 28's round number
        for that <em>same time window</em> — Round 3 of Panel 27 and Round 1 of Panel 28 happened concurrently, so
        they're referred to together as "R3/1" (variable suffix <code>31</code>). Likewise R4/2 → <code>42</code>,
        R5/3 → <code>53</code>. A variable ending in plain <code>23</code> (no round pairing) means "status as of
        December 31, 2023," combining whichever round's data applies for that person.
      </p>
      <p class="citation">Source: AHRQ, <em>2023 MEPS HC-251 Full-Year Consolidated File</em> documentation, §B/C
        1.0–2.4 and the "MEPS Panel Design: Data Reference Periods" chart (p. C-2).
        <a href="https://meps.ahrq.gov/data_stats/download_data/pufs/h251/h251doc.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">h251doc.pdf →</a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- 3. Data collection -->
    <div class="sec-label">03 · How the data is collected</div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Each household has <strong>one respondent</strong> — usually the person most knowledgeable about the
        family's health and health care — who answers for everyone in the household across all 5 rounds, via
        computer-assisted personal interviewing (CAPI). AHRQ distinguishes a few respondent roles that show up
        repeatedly in the "Survey Administration" variables:
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Reference person</span><span class="glossary-desc">The household member 16+ who owns or rents the home — the anchor identity for the household, not necessarily who answered the interview.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Respondent</span><span class="glossary-desc">Whoever actually answered the interview questions for the household that round. Usually one consistent person, but can change.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Proxy</span><span class="glossary-desc">A non-household-member who answered on the household's behalf (e.g. a caregiver), when no household member could.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">RU (Reporting Unit)</span><span class="glossary-desc">MEPS's operational grouping of people related by blood/marriage/adoption living together — the unit that gets interviewed, not always the same as "family" for analysis.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">In scope</span><span class="glossary-desc">A person counts toward national estimates only while they're part of the U.S. civilian noninstitutionalized population — someone who enters an institution, joins the military, or dies mid-year is only "in scope" for part of the year.</span></div>
      <div class="glossary-item"><span class="glossary-term">Variable name suffix "23"</span><span class="glossary-desc">Status "as of December 31, 2023" — built from whichever round's data applies, not a 6th round of its own.</span></div>
    </div>

    <!-- 4. Sample size & weighting -->
    <div class="sec-label">04 · Sample size & weighting</div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Because MEPS panels overlap and each cohort shrinks a little every round (nonresponse, dropout, people
        moving out of scope), the number of people represented in a given calendar year's file declines across
        panels. AHRQ's own reference table for this file:
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="sample-table">
      <div class="sample-row sample-head"><span>Year</span><span>Sample (N)</span></div>
      <div class="sample-row"><span>2021</span><span>27,332</span></div>
      <div class="sample-row"><span>2022</span><span>21,747</span></div>
      <div class="sample-row"><span>2023</span><span>18,463</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        This explorer's <strong>18,640</strong> figure is the inscope-respondent count before the final
        person-weight cut; <strong>18,463</strong> of those have a positive final weight
        (<code>PERWT23F</code>) and are the set AHRQ says to use for U.S.-population-level estimates. All
        statistics in this explorer are <strong>unweighted</strong> — raw respondent counts, not projected
        national totals. Weighting exists specifically to correct for the panel design's uneven sampling and
        non-response, so treat any percentage here as "share of respondents," not "share of the U.S. population."
      </p>
      <p class="citation">Source: <a href="https://meps.ahrq.gov/data_stats/download_data/pufs/h251/h251doc.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">h251doc.pdf</a> §C 2.0.</p>
    </div>

    <a href="/research/meps" class="cta-btn">Enter the Explorer →</a>

  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style is:global>
.ov-wrap {
  max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;
  padding: 0 clamp(20px, 4vw, 60px) 100px;
}
.ov-header { padding: 36px 0 24px; }
.ov-title-row { display: flex; align-items: baseline; gap: 14px; flex-wrap: wrap; margin-bottom: 12px; }
.ov-title {
  font-family: var(--serif); font-size: clamp(26px, 2.8vw, 36px);
  font-weight: 300; line-height: 1.15; color: var(--ink); margin: 0;
}
.ov-title em { font-style: italic; color: var(--rose); }
.ov-badge {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 11px; font-weight: 400;
  letter-spacing: 0.14em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--rose); border: 1px solid rgba(193,125,157,0.4);
  border-radius: 3px; padding: 2px 8px;
}
.ov-desc {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: clamp(16px, 1.6vw, 18px); font-weight: 300;
  color: var(--stone); line-height: 1.75; margin: 0;
}
.ov-desc strong { font-weight: 400; color: var(--ink); }

.sec-label {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700;
  letter-spacing: 0.01em; color: var(--rose);
  margin: 44px 0 14px;
  padding: 8px 14px;
  background: linear-gradient(to right, rgba(193,125,157,0.12), transparent 70%);
  border-radius: 4px;
}

.prose p {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 16px; font-weight: 300;
  color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.8; margin: 0 0 16px;
}
.prose strong { font-weight: 600; color: var(--ink); }
.prose em { font-style: italic; }
.prose code {
  font-family: 'SF Mono', ui-monospace, monospace; font-size: 14px;
  background: rgba(0,0,0,0.05); border-radius: 3px; padding: 1px 6px; color: var(--rose);
}
.prose .citation {
  font-size: 13px; color: var(--stone); font-style: italic; margin-top: -4px;
}
.prose .citation a { color: var(--rose); text-decoration: underline; }
.prose .citation a:hover { color: var(--ink); }

/* ── Timeline diagram ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
.timeline-card {
  border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: 8px; padding: 24px 26px 20px;
  background: var(--bg); margin: 20px 0 24px;
}
.timeline-caption {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 13px; font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink);
  margin-bottom: 18px;
}
.timeline { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 8px; }
.tl-row { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 14px; }
.tl-label {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 13px; font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink);
  width: 130px; flex-shrink: 0; line-height: 1.3;
}
.tl-label span { display: block; font-size: 11px; font-weight: 300; color: var(--stone); }
.tl-track-5 { flex: 1; display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(5, 1fr); gap: 5px; }
.tl-bar {
  height: 34px; border-radius: 4px;
  display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center;
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; color: #fff;
}
.tl-gray  { background: rgba(132,123,123,0.55); }
.tl-2023  { background: var(--rose); }
.tl-empty { background: transparent; }
.tl-pair-row { margin-top: -2px; }
.tl-pair-lbl {
  height: auto; background: transparent; color: var(--rose);
  font-size: 11px; font-weight: 500; font-style: italic;
}
.timeline-legend {
  display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; margin-top: 14px;
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 12px; color: var(--stone);
}
.tl-dot { width: 10px; height: 10px; border-radius: 2px; flex-shrink: 0; }
.tl-2023-dot { background: var(--rose); }
.timeline-note {
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 11px; font-style: italic; color: #a8a19d; margin-top: 8px;
}

/* ── Glossary ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
.glossary-grid {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(260px, 1fr));
  gap: 16px 24px;
  margin: 8px 0 8px;
}
.glossary-item { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 4px; }
.glossary-term { font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 15px; font-weight: 500; color: var(--ink); }
.glossary-desc { font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 14px; font-weight: 300; color: var(--stone); line-height: 1.6; }

/* ── Sample table ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
.sample-table {
  border: 1px solid var(--rule); border-radius: 8px; overflow: hidden; margin: 8px 0 20px;
}
.sample-row {
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
  padding: 10px 18px; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 14px; color: var(--ink);
}
.sample-row:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
.sample-row span:last-child { text-align: right; font-weight: 500; }
.sample-head {
  background: rgba(0,0,0,0.02); font-size: 11px; letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--stone); font-weight: 500;
}
.sample-head span:last-child { font-weight: 500; }

/* ── CTA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
.cta-btn {
  display: inline-block; margin-top: 24px;
  font-family: var(--sans); font-size: 15px; font-weight: 500; color: #fff;
  background: var(--rose); padding: 14px 28px; border-radius: 6px;
  text-decoration: none; transition: opacity 0.15s;
}
.cta-btn:hover { opacity: 0.85; }
</style>
